{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631872"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:34:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:34:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17402"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17402","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17402"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.09,0.76,0.03,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10092"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70573"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10092"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17402"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56037"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6692"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23618"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23634"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23690"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70573","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70573"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe renal arteries are vital vessels that supply blood to the kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes where they have originated from?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The common iliac arteries","The coeliac trunk","The abdominal aorta at L1-L2 level","Thoracic aorta at T12 level","The superior mesenteric artery"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal arteries arise from the abdominal aorta at the level of L1-L2 vertebrae\u003C/strong\u003E. They branch laterally from the aorta at approximately right angles (Image). The right renal artery is typically longer than the left due to the position of the aorta slightly to the left of midline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArise from the thoracic aorta at T12 level\u003C/strong\u003E - This level is too high; the renal arteries originate in the abdomen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArise from the common iliac arteries\u003C/strong\u003E - The common iliac arteries are too inferior and branch after the aortic bifurcation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArise from the superior mesenteric artery\u003C/strong\u003E - While the superior mesenteric artery also branches from the abdominal aorta, it does not give rise to the renal arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArise from the coeliac trunk\u003C/strong\u003E - The coeliac trunk supplies the foregut derivatives and does not give rise to the renal arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter arising from the aorta, each renal artery divides into anterior and posterior branches before entering the renal hilum. The anterior branch typically supplies three renal segments, while the posterior branch supplies one segment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The renal arteries arise from the abdominal aorta at the level of the first and second lumbar vertebrae.","The right renal artery is typically longer than the left due to the position of the aorta to the left of midline.","The renal arteries divide into anterior and posterior branches before entering the renal hilum."],"referenc